plot(forecast(ar3, h = 10))

res.ar3 = ar3$residuals
tsdiag(ar3)

Box.test(res.ar3, type = "Ljung")

    Box-Ljung test

    Box-Ljung test

data:  res.ar3^2

The squared residuals are correlated. The residuals exhibit the ARCH effect.

y2 = res.ar3^2
acf(y2)

pacf(y2)

The Lag of PACF cuts off at 1. We test ARCH(1).

Do Joint Estimation Use AR(3) for the mean model, X_t

#Various hydrologic models used time series models to evaluate volatility and eliminate the ARCH effect. In modeling rainfallrunoff relationships, Modarres and Ouarda (2013) used GARCH(1,1) and ARCH(2) models. Moreover, in predicting daily streamflow, Wang, et al.(2023) used the GARCH(1,1) model. Lastly, in modeling streamflow Fathian, et al.(2019) found the ARCH(5) and ARCH(7) models to be the most fitted to their residual series.

arch1 = garchFit(~arma(3,0) + garch(1,0), data = wl_ts)
